CatDescriptText: Cutline of image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, January 1, 1955, pg. 1, reads: "Collect for Life-Giving Oxygen - Florence and Eugene Young, ages 11 and 8, respectively read a story in Dec. 11 issues of the Courier about a little girl, Aguila Foster, in Youngstown, who is being kept alive by a daily injection of oxygen which costs $8.50 per service which her poor parents are unable to pay. The youngsters, shown above, started collecting money on their own by door-to-door solicitation and asking everyone they met to help keep the little Foster girl alive.  They collected $13, mostly in pennies, and brought it to the Courier to be turned over to the ill child's parents. - Harris Photo."
TitMainTitle: Florence and Eugene Young collecting money for Aquilla Foster
